# .dockerignore — pruning the build context for container/Dockerfile.
#
# The container/Dockerfile builds claude-watch from local working-tree
# sources via a top-level `COPY . /build` in its claude-watch-builder
# stage (replacing the prior git-clone-and-pin pattern). The build
# context is the repo root, so without this file Docker would ship
# every byte under the repo to the daemon — including the Rust
# `target/` tree (hundreds of MB of incremental build artifacts),
# Python venvs, OS-side caches, and worktree scratch dirs. That makes
# `docker build` painfully slow even when nothing has changed, and
# invalidates the COPY layer on every cargo run.
#
# Anything baked into the image via a specific COPY (container/*,
# tools/hooks/*, tools/obligations/*, tools/agent-msg/*, tools/agent-tail/*,
# tools/claude-watch-ack/*, tools/claude-watch-dispatch/*, tools/watchers/*,
# tools/session-task/*) MUST remain visible — those COPY lines reference
# explicit paths and the Dockerfile would fail if the path were excluded.
# The exclusions below target build artifacts and tooling caches that
# the image never consumes.

# Rust build output — by far the largest single source of bloat.
target/

# Python tooling caches.
__pycache__/
*.pyc
*.pyo
.pytest_cache/

# Editor / OS junk.
*.swp
*.swo
.DS_Store

# Local node tooling, virtual envs.
node_modules/
.venv/
venv/

# Coverage / profiling output.
coverage/
*.coverage
htmlcov/
.tox/
.mypy_cache/
.ruff_cache/

# Operator-specific compose override (mirrors .gitignore — keep it
# out of the image even when it's untracked locally).
examples/compose/docker-compose.override.yml

# In-tree git metadata — Cargo builds don't need it, and shipping the
# full .git/ to the daemon is wasteful (each pack file is megabytes).
.git/

# Worktree scratch space — the agent-driven workflow puts a fresh
# worktree per agent under this prefix on the host. It's never inside
# the repo on disk, but defence-in-depth is cheap.
/tmp/claude-watch-worktrees/
